The memorial, which the organizers hope to inaugurate by November, is inspired by the "engraved stones"> Stolpersteine, small brass plates placed in cities and countries across Europe in honor of individual Holocaust victims.&nbsp; The plaque will be placed in the ground at the entrance of what is still animated street of brothels and sexy shop and will include QR codes to remember the women of St Pauli whose fate is known.
&nbsp;
Sieghard Wilm, the pastor of the Lutheran church who gives the name to the neighborhood, told the Guardian that he had collaborated with residents and received the support of local sex workers to launch the project aimed at a “dignitous rhetoric”. “Millions of people visit St Pauli and every day many tourists place in front of Herbertstraße and take photos. I always found it cynical because I knew the Nazis had put the gates," he said.
&nbsp;
Wilm has defined “horrible” and a “great contradiction” the fact that the neighborhood, notoriously liberal, has so far excluded sex workers as an explicitly recognized group of Nazi victims.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2> The history of the district
Herbertstraße, a narrow alley near Reeperbahn, was born in the 19th century as a destination for local men and sailors licensed on the ground. Its refuge for the debauchery, just 60 meters long, is still a shady meeting place for pubs and weekend farewell to celibacy.
&nbsp;
The opaque metal gates, affixed with signs in German and English since the 1970s that prohibit access to women and under 18 years of age, block undiscreet looks and appear on countless Instagram feeds. The disproportionates that have been introduced into this area have been bombarded by water balloons and insults launched by the windows of the upper floors. The fences, however, were erected by the Gauleiter of Hamburg, or leader of the regional Nazi party, in 1933, when sex trade in exchange for money in Herbertstraße was considered a “sinking and shame for the community”.
&nbsp;
Between March and May 1933, Nazi officials arrested 3.201 “fornicators” >ad Hamburg, as Der Spiegel reports. Of these, 814 were taken into custody.
Although prostitution and strippers were officially banned at the time, the flourishing sexual trade of St Pauli proved impossible to close, so the authorities were content to make it invisible to passersby. Women locked up in the 1930s and 1940s remained in the Nazis’ sights as “female antisocial elements”. Many were imprisoned and deported in concentration camps. Others were subjected to forced sterilization or suicide.
