riAGI - US Secretary of State Antony Blinken> arrived at Ben Gurion Airport, near Tel Aviv, and tomorrow he will meet Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu> in Jerusalem, to discuss, among other issues, <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-30/medio-oriente-hamas-israele-rafah-262 This is the seventh visit to the region of the head of U.S. diplomacy, after the attack of Hamas on October 7. Blinken will also visit the port of Ashdod>, where humanitarian aid in the Palestinian enclave arrives, as announced by the Presidency of the Council of Ministers. Before the meeting with Netanyahu in Jerusalem, the American diplomat will be received by Israeli President Isaac Herzog>.
&nbsp;
Blinken announced that a first convoy of humanitarian aid from Jordan on Tuesday will arrive in the Strip through the Erez Pass, reopened by Israel in the north of the territory. "We are witnessing a direct link between Jordan and the north of Gaza through Erez. First loads start today," Blinken said. "This is a real and important step forward, but the road to go is still long," he added.
<div </div
The visit of the head of American diplomacy arrives at a key moment of the truce talks in the Strip, mediated by Qatar, the United States and Egypt: Tomorrow, the Islamist group Hamas is expected to respond to the last offer of truce that, according to Israeli media, include the exchange of 33 live hostages with an imprecise number of Palestinian prisoners, as well as the return of displaced Palestinians in the North of Gaza. In the evening, the Israeli liberal newspaper Haaretz, citing anonymous sources of Hamas, wrote that the organization asked for guarantees that there is a truce of several months, during which Israel does not resume attacks, as a requirement to conclude an agreement. The Jewish state will wait until Wednesday evening a response of the Palestinian movement before deciding whether to send sent to Cairo for talks on the ceasefire
&nbsp;
Waiting for a response from Hamas, Israel continues to look at Rafah. Netanyahu, in a meeting with relatives of the hostages and the fallen, reiterated the intention to launch the invasion of land against the city in the far south of Gaza, despite the harsh opposition of the U.S. and other Western allies, including France, whose foreign minister, Stephane Sejourne>, defined the plan "a bad idea" because of the "too many uncertainties on humanitarian issues". "We will enter Rafah and annihilate all Hamas battalions there, with or without a deal, to get total victory," said the head of government. "The idea that we will end the war before reaching all our objectives is unacceptable," he said.
<div </div
<h2> In U.S. occupied Columbia University</h2>
The demonstrators of the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-30/university-use-proteste-studentesche-gaza-columbia-26214819/">Columbia University</a> have barricaded within an academic building on the campus of Manhattan school, breaking windows and holding hostage some employees before releasing them. The doors of Hamilton Hall, reports the student newspaper Columbia Spectator, are closed and blocked with tables, chairs, metal barricades and other objects or are closed with locks, clamps or ropes. Tens of other protesters gathered outside, forming a human chain to block the doors and singing "From the river to the sea, Palestine will be free" and "Palestinian will live forever". Videos of the scene also show a person with a black hooded sweatshirt that splits different windows and then closes with a padlock a door after several people came out, including a person wearing kefiah and someone with a sign that identifies them as journalists.
&nbsp;
White House spokesman John Kirby called "absolutely wrong" the protest approach. The &nbsp administration has warned that students who have occupied Hamilton Hall, the historic campus building, risk expulsion for violating school rules. " Yesterday we made it clear that the work of the University cannot be interrupted infinitely by protesters who violate the rules. Continue to do so will have clear consequences: students who occupied the building risk expulsion," said Ben Chang, spokesman for the Columbia University Public Affairs Office. And he added that "it's about responding to the actions of protesters, not their cause," as these young supporters of the Palestinian cause are creating "a threatening environment" for many of the Jewish students and teachers.
&nbsp;
The assault on the building arrived a few hours after the university management announced that it began applying suspensions to students involved in campus occupation that has been going on for two weeks. For the university, the protesters chose to "aggrave" the situation "breaking doors and windows of the Hamilton Hall and blocking the entrances", so they will go ahead with "the proposed measures". "We gave everyone on campus the opportunity to leave peacefully. If they were committed to respecting University policies, they would be allowed to finish the semester," said the Public Affairs Office.
&nbsp;
Columbia protests are added to those that hundreds of students from dozens of other universities in the United States have been holding for days to protest the war in Gaza. What the demonstrations have in common is the refusal of US policy towards Israel and the invitation to schools to cut relations with the Israeli government. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
